H2:Why BAX Makes Static Sites Easy

H3:Simple Content Creation
P:BAX uses a simple .zet format that anyone can understand:

CODE:TITLE:My Post
CODE:H2:Introduction
CODE:P:This is my content.

H3:No Build Complexity
P:BAX runs with a single command:
CODE:bax.bat  # Windows
CODE:./bax.sh # Linux/Mac

H3:Cross-Platform
P:BAX runs on Windows, Linux, and macOS:
UL:
LI:No special setup
LI:No installation
LI:Just copy and run
/UL:

H3:Free Hosting Options
P:Static sites can be hosted for free:
UL:
LI:GitHub Pages
LI:Netlify
LI:Vercel
LI:Cloudflare Pages
LI:GitLab Pages
/UL:

HR:

H2:Common Myths About Static Sites

H3:Myth: Static Sites Are Old Technology
P:False. Static sites are modern and use the latest web technologies. BAX generates clean, modern HTML5.

H3:Myth: Static Sites Can't Be Dynamic
P:False. You can add JavaScript for interactivity. BAX sites can include forms, search, and dynamic features.

H3:Myth: Static Sites Are Hard to Update
P:False. With BAX, you update content by editing .zet files and rebuilding. It's faster than logging into a CMS.

H3:Myth: Static Sites Don't Scale
P:False. Static sites scale infinitely because CDNs handle the load. They handle traffic spikes better than dynamic sites.

HR:

H2:The Future of Static Sites
P:Static sites are the future of the web because:
UL:
LI:Cheaper to host
LI:Faster to load
LI:More secure
LI:Better for SEO
LI:Easier to scale
LI:More reliable
/UL:

BLOCKQUOTE:"The best way to predict the future is to create it. BAX makes creating static sites simple."

HR:

H2:Getting Started with BAX
P:Start building your static site today:

CODE:git clone https://github.com/mesinkasir/bax.git
CODE:cd bax
CODE:bax.bat  # Windows
CODE:./bax.sh # Linux/Mac

